# FlowRedux + Clean Architecture

When implementing a new feature, use [FlowRedux](https://github.com/freeletics/FlowRedux) as the state machine pattern and organize code with clean architecture boundaries.

## Required standards

- Use a `FlowReduxStateMachine` (or project-specific wrapper) for feature state and action handling.
- Keep layers separated: `presentation` -> `domain` -> `data` (dependencies point inward only).
- Put business rules and use cases in `domain`; keep framework/UI details out of `domain`.
- Keep infrastructure concerns (API, DB, storage, mappers) in `data`, exposed via domain interfaces.
- In `presentation`, dispatch actions and observe state; do not embed business logic in UI.

## Feature checklist

- Define sealed state and action models for the feature state machine.
- Add/extend use cases and repository interfaces in `domain`.
- Implement repository/data sources and mapping in `data`.
- Wire the state machine and use cases in `presentation` or DI modules.

## Quick examples

```kotlin
// ✅ GOOD: presentation delegates business logic to use case
on<RefreshAction> { _, state ->
    val items = getItemsUseCase()
    state.override { Content(items) }
}

// ❌ BAD: UI/presentation talks to API directly
on<RefreshAction> { _, state ->
    val items = api.fetchItems()
    state.override { Content(items) }
}
```
